set host names in the file below and verify:
$ cat >> /etc/hosts
192.168.1.11      db
192.168.1.11      www.google.com

so all the commands below are connecting to the same host
$ ping db
$ ssh db
$ curl http://www.google.com

if run the command below on the host:
$ hostname
host-2            //it's the actual host name, but other hosts who want to connect to this host dont care the actual name, they read the host name from /etc/hosts without judging the truth.

DNS server:
stores all the host names and matching IP addresses instead of /etc/hosts file
config the IP address of DNS server in this file /etc/resol.conf
$ cat /etc/resolv.conf
nameserver     192.168.1.100

if one IP address is set in /etc/hosts file with a host name AA and mapped another host name BB in DNS server, the system will read from the file /etc/hosts first. 
But this order can be changed, people can make it read from DNS server first followed by /etc/hosts, the file to change this order is /etc/nsswitch.conf:
$ cat /etc/nsswitch.conf
hosts:   files dns

if ping a server that is not on either list, say www.facebook.com
either:
$ cat >> /etc/resolv.conf
nameserver     192.168.1.100
nameserver     8.8.8.8
or in DNS server:
Forward All to 8.8.8.8
